### Dose titration

Of the patients entering the study, 1241 (44%) remained on their starting dose of {{ drug.name }} ({{ drug.strength }}) at visit 2, whereas 1560 (56%) patients (in accordance with the protocol requirement to uptitrate dosage if {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} was >130/85 mm Hg) had their dose increased from 40 to {{ drug.strength }} at visit 2. The {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} for these two groups (nontitrated and titrated) are shown in Table 2. For the group who responded well initially to the 40-mg dose, there was an average decrease in {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} of 21.0/13.0 mm Hg by visit 2; from visit 2 to visit 3 (the end of the study) there was a slight increase in the average {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} of 1.5/0.3 mm Hg, giving a net treatment effect of 19.5/12.7 mm Hg for the full course of 40-mg treatment. For the patients who did not respond adequately to the initial 40-mg dose, their initial decrease in {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} on {{ drug.strength }} of {{ drug.name }} averaged 7.3/4.5 mm Hg; from visit 2 to visit 3 (on a dose of {{ drug.strength }}) there was a further reduction of 7.5/5.0 mm Hg, giving an overall treatment effect of 15.0/9.5 mm Hg for the study as a whole. The final treatment effect in the nontitrated ({{ drug.strength }}) group was significantly greater than in the titrated group (40 to {{ drug.strength }}) for both systolic and diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} (P < .001 for each). As shown in Table 2, the baseline systolic and diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} in the group requiring titration were modestly but significantly greater than in the other group. Similarly, at the intermediate visit and at the final visit of the study these values were also significantly higher (P < .001 for all).

